'''''Zarzon''''' ({{nihongo2|ザルゾン}}, {{nihongo2|ザーゾン}}), also known as '''''Satan of Saturn''''' ({{nihongo2|サタン・オブ・サターン}}), is a [[1981 in video gaming|1981]] [[fixed shooter]] arcade game developed and manufactured by [[SNK]] and licensed to [[Taito]] for North American release. The gameplay is a variation of ''[[Space Invaders]]''.<ref name="Green">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=32540|title=Satan of Saturn|last=Green|first=Earl|work=[[Allgame]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]] / [[Macrovision Corporation]]|access-date=2009-06-02}} [http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=11608 version for 'Zarzon']</ref>

==Gameplay== 
[[Image:Zarzon Arcade screen shot.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Gameplay screenshot]]

The goal is to fly a spaceship to [[Saturn]], then destroy as many Satans as possible. Additional bonus points can be accumulated by destroying the [[comet]] or attacking dragonflies. An additional spaceship is rewarded if the players score reaches 5,000 or 10,000 points. If the attacking UFOs or enemy rockets are destroyed points will be scored. The game progresses through 4 different screens.

The arcade cabinet has one joystick to move the spaceship left to right and guide the missiles.

==Technical details==
The game ran on the SNK 6502 [[arcade system board]].<ref name="mame">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/master/src/mame/drivers/snk6502.c|title=SNK 6502 Hardware|website=[[MAME]]|access-date=2015-01-13}}</ref> Other games that ran on the same hardware include ''Sasuke vs. Commander'' (1980), ''[[Vanguard (video game)|Vanquard]]'' (1981) and ''[[Fantasy (video game)|Fantasy]]''.<ref name="mame"/>

==Legacy==
The ''Zarzon'' upright [[arcade cabinet]] appeared in the 1983 film ''[[Joysticks (film)|Joysticks]]''.

